        <section id="goto-technology" class="content-section">
          <h2>GoTo Technology Explained: How It Works</h2>
          <p>GoTo (short for "Go To") technology combines precision motorized mounts, onboard computers, astronomical databases, and alignment procedures to automatically point telescopes at celestial objects. Understanding how these systems work helps set realistic expectations and troubleshoot when issues arise.</p>

          <h3>Components of GoTo Systems</h3>
          <p><strong>Motorized Mount:</strong> Stepper motors on both mount axes (altitude/azimuth for Alt-Az mounts; right ascension/declination for equatorial mounts) provide precise positioning under computer control. These motors move the telescope smoothly to targets and maintain tracking as Earth rotates. Quality motors ensure smooth slewing (movement to targets), accurate positioning (typically 5-15 arcminute accuracy), and minimal vibration during operation.</p>

          <p><strong>Hand Controller:</strong> LCD display with keypad serving as user interface. Modern controllers include: databases of 30,000-40,000+ objects (Messier, NGC, IC catalogs, named stars, planets), tonight's best targets filtered by visibility, tours of seasonal highlights, custom user coordinates, and alignment wizards guiding setup. Advanced controllers add: GPS receivers for automatic location/time, electronic compass for orientation sensing, WiFi connectivity for smartphone apps, and USB ports for firmware updates.</p>

          <p><strong>Encoders:</strong> Sensors on each axis tracking mount position. High-resolution encoders (typically 4,000-10,000 steps per revolution) allow the computer to know precisely where the telescope points. When you manually move the mount (if supported), encoders update the computer's position awareness, maintaining alignment despite manual intervention. Budget GoTo systems may lack encoders, losing position knowledge if manually moved after alignment.</p>

          <p><strong>Power System:</strong> GoTo mounts require 12V DC power, typically 1-2 amps consumption (12-24 watts). Power options include: rechargeable 12V lead-acid or lithium batteries, disposable alkaline battery packs (8x AA common), AC-to-12V adapters for home use, or power banks with 12V outputs. Battery life varies—typical 7Ah battery powers mount for 6-8 hours; heavier use or cold weather reduces runtime.</p>

          <h3>Alignment Procedures</h3>
          <p>GoTo systems must align (sync computer position with sky) before accurate pointing. Alignment teaches the computer where it's located on Earth, which direction it's pointing, and how the sky currently appears. Common alignment methods:</p>

          <p><strong>1-Star Alignment:</strong> Simplest but least accurate method. Telescope automatically points at bright star (Vega, Sirius, etc.). You center the star using directional buttons, confirming alignment. Computer now knows its orientation roughly. Accuracy: 1-2 degrees typically, sufficient for low-power eyepiece fields but not high magnification. Use for quick casual observing when precision unnecessary.</p>

          <p><strong>2-Star Alignment:</strong> Standard method balancing ease and accuracy. Computer selects two bright alignment stars in different sky regions (e.g., Vega in northeast, Fomalhaut in south). You center each star precisely. Computer triangulates telescope position and orientation from this data. Accuracy: 5-15 arcminutes typical, placing most objects within eyepiece field. Requires 5-10 minutes including star identification and centering. Best for visual observing and casual use.</p>

          <p><strong>3-Star Alignment:</strong> Enhanced precision using three alignment stars. Takes slightly longer (8-12 minutes) but improves accuracy to 2-5 arcminutes, especially important for high magnification planetary observing or astrophotography. Choose alignment stars spread across sky (one east, one west, one north/south) for best results.</p>

          <p><strong>Solar System Align:</strong> Uses bright planets or Moon rather than stars. Convenient when planets visible but fewer stars (twilight, urban skies, moonlight). Accuracy comparable to star alignment. Requires identifying planets visually before initiating alignment.</p>

          <p><strong>GPS Alignment:</strong> Mounts with GPS modules automatically determine location, time, date, and orientation (via electronic compass). This eliminates manual data entry, speeds alignment, and improves accuracy. Premium feature on mid-to-high-end mounts ($800+).</p>

          <h3>Popular GoTo Systems</h3>
